E. -- tCompulsion, Volitional Disorder, and Freedom of the Will -- tRigidity: The Strange Preference for Compulsion / rLöw-Beer, Martin -- tTowards a Psychiatric Anthropology of Addiction / rSchlimme, Jann -- tNeurophilosophical Perspectives on Conservative Compatibilism / rWalter, Henrik -- tFreedom of Will, Freedom of Action and Psychiatry: Concerning the relationship of empirical to intelligible character and so-called freedom of choice in the view of forensic psychiatry / rLuthe, Rainer / Rösler, Michael -- tPersonal Identity -- tWhy Are Identity Disorders Interesting for Philosophers? / rMetzinger, Thomas -- tThe Influence of Brain Implants on Personal Identity and Personality - a Combined Theoretical and Empirical Investigation in 'Neuroethics' / rNorthoff, Georg -- tPsychiatric Ethics -- tEthics as a Focus of Controversy in Postmodern Antagonisms / rHelmchen, Hanfried -- tCompulsory Admission and Compulsory Treatment in Psychiatry / rDreßing, Harald -- tCoercive Threats and Offers in Psychiatry / rSchramme, Thomas -- tThe Moral Economics of Psychotherapy / rPawelzik, Markus / Prinz, Aloys -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhilosophie und Psychiatrie teilen viele Problemfelder und Fragestellungen. So zeitigen z.B. die "Lösungen" der Psychiatrie des philosophischen Leib-Seele-Problems direkte Auswirkungen auf das Selbstverständnis der Disziplin. Trotz dieser offensichtlichen Überschneidungen wurde im Vergleich zum angelsächsischen Sprachraum in Deutschland bislang wenig interdisziplinäre Forschung zur "philosophischen Psychopathologie" betrieben. Die vorliegende Anthologie schließt diese Lücke, denn die Autoren - sowohl ausgewiesene Fachleute als auch junge Wissenschaftler, die mit neuen Ansätzen zukunftsträchtige Perspektiven eröffnen - kommen aus beiden Disziplinen. Die einzelnen Beiträge setzen sich mit philosophischen Debatten auseinander, wie sie sich im Kontext psychiatrischer Theorie und Praxis ergeben.  aPhilosophy and psychiatry share many topics and problems. For example, the "solutions" of the psychiatry of the philosophical body-soul problem have direct effects on the self-image of the discipline. Despite these obvious overlappings, and unlike the English-speaking countries, interdisciplinary research on "philosophical psychopathology" has been scarce in Germany. The current anthology closes these gaps, because the authors - renowned experts as well as young scientists, whose new approaches open promising perspectives - come from both disciplines. The individual contributions deal with philosophical debates as they arise within the context of psychiatric theory and practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aPsychiatryxPhilosophy. 4aAufsatzsammlung. 4aPhilosophie. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPsychiatrie. 4aPsychiatry. 4aPsychotherapie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aSchramme, Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.1 aThome, Johannes, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Philosophy English Language 2000-2014z978311023848808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Philosophy 2000 - 2014z9783110636949oZDB-23-GPH0 cprintz978311017800540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110905762423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110905762.jpg  a978-3-11-023848-8  DGBA Backlist Philosophy English Language 2000-2014c2000d2014  aDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014c2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKA